{"title_page": "Archibald James Fergusson Eden (British Army officer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Archibald James Fergusson Eden\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth-date|20th January 1872|}}\n| death_date    = {{death-date|8th May 1956}}\n| birth_place   = [[Faizabad]], [[Bengal]], [[India]]\n| death_place   = [[Winchester]], [[Hampshire]]\n| allegiance    = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| branch        = [[File:Flag of the British Army.svg|23px]] [[British Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1892-\n| rank          = [[Brigadier-general (United Kingdom)|Brigadier-General]]\n| unit          = [[Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry]]\n| battles       = [[War of the Golden Stool]]\n[[Second Boer War]]\n[[World War One]]\n| awards        = [[Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Order of St Michael and St George]]\n| spouse        = Isabella Ann Weir\n| children      = Louisa Marjorie Eden,\nDorothy Isabella Eden\n| imagesize     = \n}}\n'''Archibald James Fergusson Eden''' {{post-nominals|CMG|DSO}} was a career officer in the British Army, receiving his commission in 1892 and going on to actively serve until the end of World War One, after which he remained a figure in military circles, organising memorials, overseeing parades and attending military dinners.\n\n== Early life ==\nArchibald J.F. Eden was born in Faizabad on the 20th of January 1872, the son of Major Archibald Duffield Eden and his wife Emma Louisa Jarvis, and was the oldest of three brothers, his two younger siblings being Cecil Harold Eden and Lt. Col. William Rushbrooke Eden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://family-tree.cobboldfht.com/people/view/3566|title=Family Tree - The Cobbold Family History Trust|website=family-tree.cobboldfht.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nHe was educated at [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College|Haileybury College]] from May 1885 to December 1889.\n\n== Military service ==\nEden was commissioned from the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]] on the 18th June, 1892 to be a Second Lieutenant in the Oxfordshire Light Infantry (the regiment became the Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry on 16 October 1908).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/26298/page/3517|title=London Gazette June 17, 1892, page 3517|last=|first=|date=June 17, 1892|website=The London Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== War of the Golden Stool ===\nDuring the War of the Golden Stool Eden, promoted to Captain on the 24/02/1900 after a superior was taken prisoner of war<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27179/page/2198|title=London Gazette, citation for Eden's promotion to Captain|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1900|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, in the 2nd Battalion of the [[Royal West African Frontier Force|West African Frontier Force]], was mentioned twice in the London Gazette by then Colonel Sir [[James Willcocks]] as part of his 14/08/1900 Despatch and his conduct summed up as follows: \"''This officer has shown great aptitude for commanding native soldiers; under his able guidance the Yoruba has proved himself quite equal to the Hausa; he led the charge at Kumasi. I sincerely trust he will be rewarded.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27253/page/8210|title=James Willcocks 14/08/1900 despatch RE Ashanti War|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><br />His involvement in this campaign made him eligible for the [[Ashanti Medal|Ashanti medal]] with Kumassi clasp, and he is mentioned as being one of the officers involved in ''Letters from a Bush Campaign'' by David Martineau Haylings<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haylings|first=David Martineau|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Letters_from_a_bush_campaign.html?id=-Bk1AQAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Letters from a bush campaign|date=1902*|publisher=S. H. E. Foxwell|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Second Boer War ===\nFollowing the war he was eligible for the [[Queen's South Africa Medal|Queen\u2019s South Africa Medal]] with five clasps; Cape Colony, Orange Free State, Transvaal, South Africa 1901 and South Africa 1902.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C3763955|title=National Archives Second Boer War medal rolls|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== First World War ===\nIn 1914, Eden was part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]] along with the 2nd Battalion of the Oxford and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205062220|title=THE BRITISH EXPEDITIONARY FORCE ON THE WESTERN FRONT, 1914-1915|website=Imperial War Museums|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> His medal card confirms his eligibility for the 1914 star with clasp, showing that he had been serving within at least artillery range of the German lines.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D6438977|title=Catalogue description\n                Medal card of   Eden, A J F     Corps:  Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry  ...|date=1908-1924}}</ref> \n\nStarting on the 30th of August 1918, he was in command of the [[57th Brigade (United Kingdom)|57th Brigade]], a command that lasted 67 days total, with his brigade in reserve at the [[Battle of the Sambre (1918)|Battle of the Sambre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etheses.bham.ac.uk/id/eprint/6799/9/Clayton16PhD.pdf|title=Thesis entitled THE BATTLE OF THE SAMBRE 4 NOVEMBER 1918|last=Clayton|first=John|date=September 2015|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\nPost-active service, Eden remained a figure in military activities, local politics and local historical preservation. He unveiled the Caversham War Memorial in [[Christ Church Meadow, Oxford|Christchurch Meadows]] on the 5th of May 1928<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berkshirestories.org.uk/archive/post-1918-images-berkshire/125975-the-unveiling-of-the-caversham-war-memorial-in-christchurch-meadows-5-may-1928#prettyPhoto|title=The unveiling of the Caversham War Memorial in Christchurch Meadows, 5 May 1928. - Berkshire Stories|website=berkshirestories.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, and was also Chairman of the Regimental Committee in 1931 responsible for the organisation of the memorials in the Oxford and Bucks Regimental Chapel in [[Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford]]. Circa 1945 he was the Treasurer of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] Winchester branch<ref>{{Cite book|last=Thorpe|first=Andrew|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BK8UDAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA98&dq=ajf%20eden&pg=PA98#v=twopage&q=ajf%20eden&f=true|title=Parties at War: Political Organization in Second World War Britain|date=2009-01-08|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-927273-0|language=en}}</ref>, and circa 1953 he was a member of the Hampshire Field Club and Archaeological Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hantsfieldclub.org.uk/publications/hampshirestudies/digital/1940s/vol17/Other_material_pt3.pdf|title=Hampshire Field Club and Archaeological Society members list 1953|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe died on the 8th of May, 1956, aged 84.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[:Category:Second Boer War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n| name          = Archibald James Fergusson Eden\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth-date|1872|}}\n| death_date    = {{death-date|8th May 1956}}\n| birth_place   = [[Faizabad]], [[Bengal]], [[India]]\n| death_place   = [[Winchester]], [[Hampshire]]\n| allegiance    = {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| branch        = [[File:Flag of the British Army.svg|23px]] [[British Army]]\n| serviceyears  = 1892-\n| rank          = [[Brigadier-general (United Kingdom)|Brigadier-General]]\n| unit          = [[Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry]]\n| battles       = [[War of the Golden Stool]]\n[[Second Boer War]]\n[[World War One]]\n| awards        = [[Distinguished Service Order]]\n[[Order of St Michael and St George]]\n| spouse        = Isabella Ann Weir\n| children      = Louisa Marjorie Eden,\nDorothy Isabella Eden\n| imagesize     = \n}}\n'''Archibald James Fergusson Eden''' {{post-nominals|CMG|DSO}} was a career officer in the British Army, receiving his commission in 1892 and going on to actively serve until the end of World War One, after which he remained a figure in military circles, organising memorials, overseeing parades and attending military dinners.\n\n== Early life ==\nArchibald J.F. Eden was born in Faizabad 1872, the son of Major Archibald Duffield Eden and his wife Emma Louisa Jarvis, and was the oldest of three brothers, his two younger siblings being Cecil Harold Eden and Lt. Col. William Rushbrooke Eden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://family-tree.cobboldfht.com/people/view/3566|title=Family Tree - The Cobbold Family History Trust|website=family-tree.cobboldfht.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Military service ==\nEden was commissioned from the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]] on the 18th June, 1892 to be a Second Lieutenant in the Oxfordshire Light Infantry (the regiment became the Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry on 16 October 1908).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/26298/page/3517|title=London Gazette June 17, 1892, page 3517|last=|first=|date=June 17, 1892|website=The London Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== War of the Golden Stool ===\nDuring the War of the Golden Stool Eden, promoted to Captain on the 24/02/1900 after a superior was taken prisoner of war<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27179/page/2198|title=London Gazette, citation for Eden's promotion to Captain|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1900|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, in the 2nd Battalion of the [[Royal West African Frontier Force|West African Frontier Force]], was mentioned twice in the London Gazette by then Colonel Sir [[James Willcocks]] as part of his 14/08/1900 Despatch and his conduct summed up as follows: \"''This officer has shown great aptitude for commanding native soldiers; under his able guidance the Yoruba has proved himself quite equal to the Hausa; he led the charge at Kumasi. I sincerely trust he will be rewarded.''\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/27253/page/8210|title=James Willcocks 14/08/1900 despatch RE Ashanti War|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><br />His involvement in this campaign made him eligible for the [[Ashanti Medal|Ashanti medal]] with Kumassi clasp, and he is mentioned as being one of the officers involved in ''Letters from a Bush Campaign'' by David Martineau Haylings<ref>{{Cite book|last=Haylings|first=David Martineau|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Letters_from_a_bush_campaign.html?id=-Bk1AQAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Letters from a bush campaign|date=1902*|publisher=S. H. E. Foxwell|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Second Boer War ===\nFollowing the war he was eligible for the [[Queen's South Africa Medal|Queen\u2019s South Africa Medal]] with five clasps; Cape Colony, Orange Free State, Transvaal, South Africa 1901 and South Africa 1902.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/C3763955|title=National Archives Second Boer War medal rolls|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== First World War ===\nIn 1914, Eden was part of the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War I)|British Expeditionary Force]] along with the 2nd Battalion of the Oxford and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/205062220|title=THE BRITISH EXPEDITIONARY FORCE ON THE WESTERN FRONT, 1914-1915|website=Imperial War Museums|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> His medal card confirms his eligibility for the 1914 star with clasp, showing that he had been serving within at least artillery range of the German lines.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/r/D6438977|title=Catalogue description\n                Medal card of   Eden, A J F     Corps:  Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry  ...|date=1908-1924}}</ref> \n\nStarting on the 30th of August 1918, he was in command of the [[57th Brigade (United Kingdom)|57th Brigade]], a command that lasted 67 days total, with his brigade in reserve at the [[Battle of the Sambre (1918)|Battle of the Sambre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://etheses.bham.ac.uk/id/eprint/6799/9/Clayton16PhD.pdf|title=Thesis entitled THE BATTLE OF THE SAMBRE 4 NOVEMBER 1918|last=Clayton|first=John|date=September 2015|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Later life ==\nPost-active service, Eden remained a figure in military activities, local politics and local historical preservation. He unveiled the Caversham War Memorial in [[Christ Church Meadow, Oxford|Christchurch Meadows]] on the 5th of May 1928<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://berkshirestories.org.uk/archive/post-1918-images-berkshire/125975-the-unveiling-of-the-caversham-war-memorial-in-christchurch-meadows-5-may-1928#prettyPhoto|title=The unveiling of the Caversham War Memorial in Christchurch Meadows, 5 May 1928. - Berkshire Stories|website=berkshirestories.org.uk|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>, and was also Chairman of the Regimental Committee in 1931 responsible for the organisation of the memorials in the Oxford and Bucks Regimental Chapel in [[Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford]]. Circa 1945 he was the Treasurer of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] Winchester branch<ref>{{Cite book|last=Thorpe|first=Andrew|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=BK8UDAAAQBAJ&lpg=PA98&dq=ajf%20eden&pg=PA98#v=twopage&q=ajf%20eden&f=true|title=Parties at War: Political Organization in Second World War Britain|date=2009-01-08|publisher=OUP Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-927273-0|language=en}}</ref>, and circa 1953 he was a member of the Hampshire Field Club and Archaeological Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hantsfieldclub.org.uk/publications/hampshirestudies/digital/1940s/vol17/Other_material_pt3.pdf|title=Hampshire Field Club and Archaeological Society members list 1953|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe died on the 8th of May, 1956, aged 84.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[:Category:Second Boer War]]\n", "name_user": "Vexed Cassidy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archibald_James_Fergusson_Eden_(British_Army_officer)"}
